  <!-- What is Spray Foam Insulation -->
  <section id="what-is-spray-foam" class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">What is Spray Foam Insulation?</h2>
    <div class="prose max-w-none">
      <p class="text-lg mb-4">Spray foam insulation is a cutting-edge polyurethane-based material that expands upon application to create an airtight seal in walls, attics, crawl spaces, and other areas of your Phoenix home. Unlike traditional insulation materials like fiberglass batts or blown-in cellulose, spray foam provides both insulation and air sealing in a single application.</p>
      
      <p class="mb-4">This revolutionary insulation technology has become increasingly popular in Arizona due to its superior performance in extreme heat conditions. When professionally installed by certified contractors like ICA, spray foam creates a continuous thermal barrier that dramatically reduces energy consumption and improves indoor comfort.</p>

      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">The Science Behind Spray Foam</h3>
      <p class="mb-4">Spray foam insulation is created through a chemical reaction between two components: isocyanate and polyol resin. When these materials are mixed at the application nozzle, they react and expand to fill every crack, gap, and void in the building envelope. This expansion can range from 30 to 100 times the original volume, depending on whether you're using open-cell or closed-cell foam.</p>

      <p class="mb-4">The cellular structure of spray foam creates millions of tiny air pockets that resist heat transfer through conduction, convection, and radiation. This triple-action protection makes spray foam particularly effective in Phoenix's harsh desert climate, where temperatures regularly exceed 110Â°F in summer.</p>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 p-6 rounded-lg my-8">
        <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Key Components of Spray Foam:</h4>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Isocyanate (A-side):</strong> Provides structural integrity and chemical resistance</li>
          <li><strong>Polyol Resin (B-side):</strong> Contains polyols, catalysts, blowing agents, and fire retardants</li>
          <li><strong>Blowing Agents:</strong> Create the cellular structure (water for open-cell, HFCs for closed-cell)</li>
          <li><strong>Fire Retardants:</strong> Ensure compliance with building codes</li>
          <li><strong>Surfactants:</strong> Control cell size and structure</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">How Spray Foam Differs from Traditional Insulation</h3>
      <p class="mb-4">Traditional insulation materials like fiberglass and cellulose work primarily by trapping air in their fibrous structure. However, they don't prevent air movement through the material itself. In contrast, spray foam creates an impermeable barrier that stops air infiltration completely.</p>

      <p class="mb-4">This fundamental difference is crucial in Phoenix, where hot outdoor air infiltration can overwhelm HVAC systems. Studies show that up to 40% of a building's energy loss is due to air infiltration, making spray foam's air-sealing properties invaluable for Arizona homeowners.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

